---

<BaseLayout
  title="Bucket Elevators: Centrifugal, Continuous & Internal Discharge"
  description="Complete guide to bucket elevators: centrifugal discharge, continuous discharge, internal discharge. Capacity, lift height, belt vs chain, and selection for bulk material handling."
  canonical="https://packagingconveyor.com/conveyor-types/bucket-elevators/"
  schema={[breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema, articleSchema]}
>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav class="bg-surface border-b border-border" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-3">
      <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-ink-muted">
        <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Home</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/conveyor-types/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Conveyor Types</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Bucket Elevators</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Bucket Elevators</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Bucket Elevators
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A bucket elevator lifts bulk materials vertically using a series of buckets attached to a belt or chain that loops around head (top) and boot (bottom) pulleys inside an enclosed casing. Bucket elevators are the most efficient method for vertical bulk material transport, lifting grain, cement, ore, chemicals, and <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food ingredients</a> from 20 to 200+ feet. The three discharge types , centrifugal, continuous, and internal , handle different material characteristics and throughput requirements.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Centrifugal Discharge -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="centrifugal-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Centrifugal Discharge</div>
      <h2 id="centrifugal-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Centrifugal Discharge <span class="text-accent">Elevators</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Centrifugal discharge bucket elevators run at high speed (200-500 FPM belt speed). Buckets are spaced apart on the belt, with gaps between buckets. As each bucket passes over the head pulley, centrifugal force throws the material out of the bucket and into the discharge chute. The material trajectory follows a parabolic path from the bucket lip to the discharge opening.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Operating Principle</h3>
        <p>At the boot (bottom), buckets scoop material from the boot pit or receive material from an infeed chute. The loaded buckets travel up the vertical leg. At the head (top), the high belt speed generates enough centrifugal force to overcome gravity as the bucket inverts around the head pulley. The material releases from the bucket and flies into the discharge throat. Proper discharge depends on the relationship between belt speed, head pulley diameter, and material characteristics.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Best Applications</h3>
        <p>Centrifugal discharge suits free-flowing, non-fragile materials: grain, dry sand, cement, sugar, salt, and plastic pellets. The high speed and centrifugal discharge generate some material impact and degradation, making this type less suitable for fragile products. Centrifugal elevators deliver the highest capacity per belt width: 10-1,000+ tons per hour depending on belt width and speed. They dominate grain elevator and cement plant applications.</p>
        <p>Maxi-Lift, Tapco, 4B Components, and Continental/Contitech supply centrifugal discharge elevator buckets and belting. System integrators including Sweet Manufacturing, Warrior Manufacturing, and Universal Industries build complete centrifugal discharge elevator systems.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Maxi-Lift, Tapco, 4B, Sweet, Warrior, Universal current product offerings -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Belt vs Chain</h3>
        <p>Centrifugal discharge elevators use either rubber/PVC belting or roller chain to carry the buckets. Belt elevators are quieter, lighter, and less expensive. Chain elevators handle higher temperatures, heavier materials, and more abrasive conditions. Belt elevators dominate grain and food applications. Chain elevators serve cement, mining, and heavy industrial applications.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Continuous Discharge -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="continuous-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Continuous Discharge</div>
      <h2 id="continuous-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Continuous Discharge <span class="text-accent">Elevators</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Continuous discharge (also called positive discharge) bucket elevators run at lower speed (100-200 FPM) with buckets mounted back-to-back without gaps. Material discharges by gravity as each bucket inverts over the head pulley. The front lip of each bucket acts as a guide for the material sliding out of the bucket above it, creating a continuous flow of material from the buckets into the discharge chute.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Gentle Handling</h3>
        <p>The lower speed and gravity discharge minimize material impact and degradation. Continuous discharge elevators handle fragile materials: breakfast cereals, snack foods, pet food kibble, pharmaceutical tablets, and decorative coatings. Material breakage is significantly lower than centrifugal discharge elevators. For the gentlest vertical lift, continuous discharge bucket elevators outperform <a href="/conveyor-types/screw-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">vertical screw conveyors</a> and most pneumatic systems.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Sluggish Materials</h3>
        <p>Continuous discharge also handles materials that do not release cleanly from buckets under centrifugal force: damp powders, sticky materials, and materials with high angle of repose. The slow inversion and gravity pour provide more time for complete bucket emptying. Bucket design variations (round-bottom, V-shaped, flared) optimize discharge for specific material characteristics.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Capacity</h3>
        <p>Continuous discharge elevators handle lower capacity per belt width than centrifugal types because the lower belt speed means fewer bucket loads per minute. Compensate by using wider belts, deeper buckets, or running two elevators in parallel. Typical capacity: 5-200 tons per hour. For applications where material quality matters more than throughput rate, continuous discharge is the standard choice.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Internal Discharge -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="internal-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Internal Discharge</div>
      <h2 id="internal-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Internal Discharge <span class="text-accent">Elevators</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Internal discharge (also called perfect discharge) bucket elevators use special bucket mounting that allows buckets to tip completely upside down over the head pulley, pouring material into a trough or chute inside the elevator casing. The buckets mount on two chains (dual-chain configuration) with snug pivots that allow controlled tipping. Material empties into an internal discharge trough that routes it out through the side of the elevator casing.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Complete Discharge</h3>
        <p>Internal discharge provides the most complete bucket emptying of any elevator type. The full inversion and slow pour leave virtually no residual material in the bucket. This matters for high-value materials, materials that build up on bucket walls, and operations requiring minimal cross-contamination between batches. Pharmaceutical, chemical, and specialty food operations use internal discharge elevators.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Limitations</h3>
        <p>Internal discharge elevators use dual-chain construction, which costs more than single-belt or single-chain designs. The internal discharge trough adds complexity to the head section. Capacity is moderate: similar to continuous discharge types. Internal discharge elevators are specified when discharge completeness justifies the added cost , typically in batch operations where residual material between batches is unacceptable.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
