      <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How to Select a <span class="text-accent">Bucket Elevator</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Material characteristics determine discharge type.</strong> Free-flowing, non-fragile: centrifugal discharge. Fragile, sluggish, or damp: continuous discharge. High-value with zero residual tolerance: internal discharge. Test material behavior in sample buckets if material characteristics are uncertain.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Capacity and lift height size the elevator.</strong> Calculate required tons per hour. Select bucket size (width, projection, spacing) and belt speed to achieve the capacity. Belt width and casing size scale with bucket size. Lift height determines belt length, casing height, and structural support requirements. CEMA standards provide capacity calculation methods based on bucket geometry and material bulk density.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Belt vs chain depends on environment.</strong> Belt: clean, moderate-temperature, non-abrasive (grain, food, light chemicals). Chain: high-temperature, abrasive, heavy-duty (cement, mining, hot materials). Belt elevators cost less, run quieter, and need less maintenance. Chain elevators last longer in harsh conditions. Hybrid designs use chain with belt-type buckets for moderate applications.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Safety systems are mandatory.</strong> Bucket elevators require: speed monitoring (detecting belt slip or chain breakage), bearing temperature monitoring (detecting imminent bearing failure), belt alignment monitoring (preventing belt tracking off the pulley), and explosion protection for combustible dusts (venting, suppression, or inerting). NFPA 61 (grain) and NFPA 652 (combustible dust) govern bucket elevator safety design.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: NFPA 61 and 652 applicability to bucket elevator safety design -->

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Compared to alternatives:</strong> Bucket elevators beat <a href="/conveyor-types/screw-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">vertical screw conveyors</a> on capacity, gentleness, and lift height. They beat incline belt conveyors on footprint (vertical vs angled). They beat pneumatic systems on energy efficiency and material preservation. <a href="/conveyor-types/spiral-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Spiral conveyors</a> serve unit loads (cases, cartons); bucket elevators serve bulk materials. Choose bucket elevators for vertical bulk transport unless a specific constraint disqualifies them.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
